                        <interp inst="t18401019-name-1016" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN ELLIOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a pawnbroker, in the Kingsland-road. On the 12th of October I saw the prisoner Pearson—I did not see the other two.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18401019-name-1017" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18401019-name-1017" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18401019-name-1017" type="surname" value="TURPIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18401019-name-1017" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY TURPIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I apprehended Mills on Monday</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184010190135"></xptr>
               <p>last, and asked if he knew what 1 was come for—he said, Yes, hand<lb></lb>kerchiefs, he supposed—I am sure of that—as we were going to the sta<lb></lb>tion-house, he said he was going with Pearson and Nixon into the country to pick blackberries, when they came to a gentleman's lawn, and saw these handkerchiefs on it—that he went in with Pearson, that he took two of the handkerchiefs off the line himself, and Pearson took the other, and Dixon remained outside in the road to watch—I took Dixon—he laid that they had pawned the two, and sold the other in Petticoat-lane, and received 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a-piece—he described the place, which was the premises of Mr. Child.</p>
